br>    <BR><img src=http://www.angelfire.com/pop/cdoss/dances2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: the blame game</span><hr size=1> IMO Shawnee this article states the man wrote in, that is why maybe the subject has turned that way.<br>
<br>
In all honesty if the woman wrote in I would be saying the same damn thing.  EQ had nothing to do with my marriage falling apart,  My husband and I did.  In our situation we have united an alcoholic with some one who doesnt drink, make any sense?  My husband has his beer I have my game, the big difference here is that I am willing to shut the computer off if he would turn the tap off.<br>
<br>
In the begining maybe I was a bit addicted who know's, but right at this stage of the game, I can deffinetly say I am not.<br>
I would love for my husband to get interested in the game or to share a hobby with me, but I will not share his hobby, that is to drink.  Would I be condemed for this?<br>
<br>
My point (I think lol) is that if I was totaly content or even partialy happy I would not be online.  Now this is not saying that goes for other people, if I had a spouse who loved playing EQ , Sweeet:)   Same as if they wanted to golf or garden I would love to be able to have quality time, in what ever way we both would enjoy ourselves.<br>
<br>
The husband in this letter should stand back and ask himself why his wife is calling other men.  Same thing if it was a male gamer.  Why is she more interested in staying online then being with him?  Obiviously there is more to the story, there always is. <p><br>
